DeepMetal: An Intelligent Metal Recommendation System¶

TDI Capstone Proposal¶

Alexander Sack¶

pisymbol@gmail.com¶

November 2018¶

Overview¶

  • Combine my passion for music with data science

  • Leverage the latest technologies in natural lanuage processing (NLP) and deep learning

  • TDI Challenge Case Study: "Angry Metal-AI"

  • Roadmap

Why DeepMetal?¶

  • Sentiment analysis (or opinion mining) is one of the oldest forms of NLP and a technique that has a wide range of applications (e.g. business intelligence, product recommendations, branding, social media metrics, market fundamental analysis)

  • Keeping it personal: I'm a founder of the website Metal-Fi and a guest writer for Angry Metal-Guy.

  • Demonstrate my ability to apply modern data science techniques and have a head-banging good time doing so.

"Angry Metal-AI"¶

  • Angry Metal Guy, one the most popular metal sites on the web with over a million views per month.

  • It's a reviewed based blog where new metal records are scored by its staff on a five point scale in half point increments.

  • Built multiple sentiment analysis classifiers using Naive Bayes (sklearn) and deep learning (keras/Tensorflow, RNNs, GloVE/word2vec)

# Extract the review's rating from content. It takes precedence over what was tagged
# since that is what readers see on the site.

rating_regex = re.compile(r'.*(Rating:|Rating [-|]|Score:)\s*(\d(\.\d+)?)(\/(\d+(\.\d)?))?')
ratings = []
for i in df.index:
    rating = np.nan
    mobj = rating_regex.search(df.loc[i, 'review'])
    if mobj:
        rating = mobj.group(2)
    ratings.append(rating)
df['rating'] = pd.Series(pd.to_numeric(ratings))

# Multi reviews are terribly indexed (read: not indexed) on AMG. A multi review is a review
# that contains two or more embedded reviews/ratings for a particular release.
#
# What we do here is for each multi review, we take the arithmetic mean of the embedded reviews
# as the final rating score. This obviously has the by product of mincing words between authors but
# that's OK since our model is meant to be author agnostic.
ratings = []
for i in df.index:
    words = df.loc[i, 'review'].split()
    matches = re.findall(r'.*(Rating:|Rating [-|]|Score:)(.*)\s*', df.loc[i, 'review'])
    if len(matches) > 1:
        ratings = []
        for match in matches:
            mobj = re.search(r'\s*(\d(\.\d+)?)(\/(\d+(\.\d)?))?', match[1])
            if mobj:
                ratings.append(mobj.group(1))
        if len(ratings) > 1:
            mean = np.mean(list(map(float, ratings)))
            print(i, df.loc[i, 'title'], ratings, mean)
            df.loc[i, 'rating'] = mean

# Technically speaking, AMG's ratings are matched to certain words:
#
# Rating System
# 5.0 - Perfect
# 4.5 - Excellent
# 4.0 - Great
# 3.5 - Very Good
# 3.0 - Good
# 2.5 - Mixed
# 2.0 - Disappointing
# 1.5 - Bad
# 1.0 - Embarrassing
# 0.5 - Pathetic
# 0.0 - Worthless
#
# Let's do another pass but this time convert the rating word)(s) to a score
word2rating = {
                'Perfect' : 5.0,
                'Excellent': 4.5,
                'Great': 4.0,
                'Very Good': 3.5,
                'Good': 3.0,
                'Mixed': 2.5,
                'Disappointing': 2.0,
                'Bad': 1.5,
                'Embarrassing': 1.0,
                'Pathetic': 0.5,
                'Worthless': 0.0
}

for unrated in unrated_indexes:
    mobj = re.search(r'.*(Rating:|Rating [-|]|Score:)(.*)\s*', df.loc[unrated, 'review'])
    if mobj:
        # Remember that we are filtering UTF-8 encoded strings so normalize
        # before casefolding below.
        wordRating = unicodedata.normalize('NFKD', mobj.group(2)).strip()
        wordRating = wordRating.strip('!')
        if unrated == 1982:
            r1982 = wordRating
        foundRating = False
        for key, value in word2rating.items():
            if key.casefold() == wordRating.casefold():
                df.loc[unrated, 'rating'] = value
                foundRating = True
                break
        if not foundRating:
            print(unrated, wordRating)

# Now extract the words from the reviews, remove stop words and stem.
def review2words(review, stem=True):
    regex = re.compile('[^a-zA-Z]')
    text = regex.sub(' ', review)
    words = text.lower().strip().split()
    words = [word for word in words if word not in stopwords.words('english')]
    if stem:
        words = [stemmer.stem(word) for word in words]

    return " ".join(words)
df['words'] = df['review'].apply(review2words)
df['words_cnt'] = df['words'].apply(lambda x: len(x.split(' ')))

In [103]:
def prepare_amg_data(data):
    """Prepare training and test sets from AMG reviews."""
    
    data_train = data['train']['pos']+data['train']['neg']
    data_test = data['test']['pos']+data['test']['neg']
    labels_train = [1]*len(data['train']['pos'])+[0]*len(data['train']['neg'])
    labels_test = [1]*len(data['test']['pos'])+[0]*len(data['test']['neg'])
    data_train, labels_train = shuffle(data_train, labels_train)
    data_test, labels_test = shuffle(data_test, labels_test)
    
    # Return a unified training data, test data, training labels, test labets
    return data_train, data_test, labels_train, labels_test

data_train, data_test, labels_train, labels_test = prepare_amg_data(data)
print("AMG reviews (combined): train = {}, test = {}".format(len(data_train), len(data_test)))

AMG reviews (combined): train = 2602, test = 650

--- Raw review ---
Being the traditional kind of guy I am, if you were to tell me there was a band taking the very best parts of vintage Candlemass and Tad Morose and expertly welding them together, you would have my undivided attention. Below is that act, and Upon a Pale Horse is their second opus of epic doom mixed with classic/traditional metal. Mystery abounds as to how we whiffed on their 2014 debut, Across the Dark River, but we did and it was a mistake we won't be making again. You see, Below has that "Wow factor" we reviewers scour promo bins in search of. They write monolithic yet highly accessible doom tunes sure to captivate fans of albums like Nightfall and Ancient Dreams, as well as disciples of the works of Tad Morose, Lefay and other such traditional metal masters. Slick songwriting, wicked talent and a righteous ear for emotion and hooks make for a sure fire success, and it's easy to mistake this young band for a much more seasoned, experienced ensemble.
Things take off steeply with opener "Disappearing Into Nothing" assaulting you with wicked doom riffs ripped right from Leif Edling's subconscious. When Zeb's (Sebastion Jansson) vocals pierce through the fog you'll know you stumbled into a doom wonderland. The man has a big set of pipes and channels Rob Lowe (Solitude Aeturnus) and Urban Breed (ex-Tad Morose, ex-Bloodbound) in equal measures as he takes the solid doom foundation to an altogether higher plane of misery and depression. The song's chorus is huge and far catchier than doom should ever be. Follow up "The Coven" keeps things heavy, reminding me a lot of the material on Tad Morose's A Mended Rhyme album, but darker and more doom-centric.
The title track is nearly 10-minutes but never feels it as the band delivers first-rate brooding, epical doom that goes heavy on mood and heavier still on emotion. Borrowing at various times from IronMaiden, Candlemass, and Primordial, the song feels irresistible in its power and scope and Zeb delivers a hard, rough-edged Urban Breed style performance sure to impress. "Suffer in Silence" is much more direct and urgent, like a punch to the jaw with brass knuckles, with crunchy riffs laying on your chest with rib-cracking heft. "1000 Broken Bones" sounds like it was taken directly from Tad Morose's excellentUndead album with a grim, moody, riff-driven approach; and emotive closer "We Are All Slaves" bowls you over with its deeply brooding, emotionally draining journey full of nods to DoomVS and the long underappreciated Communic.

All seven songs are top-notch examples of melodic doom and the album feels much shorter than its 47 minutes because the writing is so strong. The production is also solid and satisfyingly deep, with real heaviness in the riffs and a sweetly organic drums sound.
Mr. Zeb is big find and his vocals are a major part of Below's appeal. His range is impressive and his rough-edged delivery is a perfect fit with the doomy, downtrodden riffage and bleak mood. His vocals on oversized epics like "Disappearing Into Nothing" and the title track show a keen knack for dramatics and theater without every crossing into overwrought overkill or cheese-play. The guitar-work by Berg and Paud is also impeccably rendered. They both graduated magna cum loud from Candlemass U. and the influence of that iconic band lives large in their dirgy leads, melodic soloing and overall song structuring. Of special note is the drumming by Doc (Jens Vestergren). His style has a heavy groove and swagger even when he's in minimalist mode on the slower segments and his kit work delivers a whole lotta pop to the proceedings when things get busy. And busy things get, as tempos change frequently, never relying too much on standard doom chugs. This makes the album much more aggressive and lively while staving off boredom throughout.
Below's debut was rock solid, but their sophomore outing is better, proving beyond a doubt they can play with the big boys.Upon a Pale Horse is on a fast track to year-end listery and is almost certainly one of the best doom albums of 2017. Below is now above.

tokenizer.fit_on_texts(texts)
sequences = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences(texts)

word_index = tokenizer.word_index
data = pad_sequences(sequences, maxlen=maxlen)

# We will shuffle indexes randomly and then split into
# training, validation, and test sets respectively.
indices = np.arange(data.shape[0])
np.random.shuffle(indices)
data = data[indices]
labels = labels[indices]
sent_labels = sent_labels[indices]

# Train
x_train = data[:training_samples]
y_train = labels[:training_samples]
y_sent_train = sent_labels[:training_samples]

# Validation
x_val = data[training_samples: training_samples + validation_samples]
y_val = labels[training_samples: training_samples + validation_samples]
y_sent_val = sent_labels[training_samples: training_samples + validation_samples]

# Test
x_test = data[training_samples + validation_samples:]
y_test = labels[training_samples + validation_samples:]
y_sent_test = sent_labels[training_samples + validation_samples:]

# Print a summary
print('Found %s unique tokens.' % len(word_index))
print('Shape of data:', data.shape)
print('Shape of labels:', labels.shape)
print('Shape of sentiment labels:', sent_labels.shape)
print('Number of training samples:', len(x_train))
print('Number of validation samples:', len(x_val))
print('Number of test samples:', len(x_test))

# Let's use a GLoVE embedding since we don't have a lot of data to build our own embedding layer
data_dir = 'data'
glove_dir = os.path.join(data_dir, 'glove6B')
if not os.path.exists(glove_dir):
    os.mkdir(glove_dir)
glove_file = os.path.join(glove_dir, 'glove.6B.zip')
url = 'http://nlp.stanford.edu/data/glove.6B.zip'
if not os.path.exists(glove_file):
    print("Downloading {0}...".format(url), end="")
    urllib.request.urlretrieve(url, glove_file)
    print("done")
    print("Extracting...", end="")
    glove_zip = zipfile.ZipFile(glove_file, 'r')
    glove_zip.extractall(glove_dir)
    glove_zip.close()
    print("done")
else:
    print("glove6B already installed...")

embeddings_dim = 300
embeddings_index = {}
embeddings_matrix = np.zeros((max_words, embeddings_dim))
with open(os.path.join(glove_dir, 'glove.6B.300d.txt'), encoding='utf-8') as f:
    for line in f:
        values = line.split()
        word = values[0]
        coefs = np.asarray(values[1:], dtype='float32')
        embeddings_index[word] = coefs

# Generic function to graph accuracy and loss of various different models
def graph_model(history):
    acc = history.history['acc']
    val_acc = history.history['val_acc']
    loss = history.history['loss']
    val_loss = history.history['val_loss']
    epochs = range(1, len(acc) + 1)

    plt.plot(epochs, acc, 'bo', label='Training acc')
    plt.plot(epochs, val_acc, 'b', label='Validation acc')
    plt.title('Training and validation accuracy')
    plt.legend()
    plt.figure()
    plt.plot(epochs, loss, 'bo', label='Training loss')
    plt.plot(epochs, val_loss, 'b', label='Validation loss')
    plt.title('Training and validation loss')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

# Sentiment analysis with GLoVE embeddings
model = Sequential()
model.add(Embedding(max_words, embeddings_dim, input_length=maxlen))
model.add(Flatten())
model.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
model.summary()
# Use GLoVE embeddings instead of trying to learn them on the fly
model.layers[0].set_weights([embeddings_matrix])
model.layers[0].trainable = False
model.compile(optimizer='rmsprop',
              loss='binary_crossentropy',
              metrics=['acc'])
history = model.fit(x_train, y_sent_train,
                    epochs=10,
                    batch_size=32,
                    validation_data=(x_val, y_sent_val))
graph_model(history)
model.save_weights('data/pre_trained_sent_glove_model.h5')
model.evaluate(x_test, y_sent_test)
